# Comments

## Default: Don't Comment
Well-named functions, variables, and types are the documentation.
If you feel the urge to comment, first try to make the code clearer.
```go
// Bad — comment restates what the code says
// get user by id
user, err := getUserByID(id)

// Good — no comment needed, code is self-evident
user, err := getUserByID(id)
```

## When to Comment
Only comment when the code cannot express the intent on its own:

- **Why, not what** — explain non-obvious decisions, tradeoffs, or constraints.
- **Workarounds** — document why a hack exists and what it's working around.
- **External references** — link to a spec, RFC, ticket, or bug that explains the context.
- **Surprising behavior** — warn about a non-obvious edge case or gotcha.
```go
// Retry limit matches the upstream API's documented backoff window (see JIRA-1234)
const maxRetries = 7

// sync.Map used here — profiling showed mutex contention at >10k rps
var cache sync.Map
```

## Never Comment
- What the code does — the code says that.
- Function signatures, parameter names, or return types that are already clear.
- Noise markers: `// end of loop`, `// constructor`, `// helper`.
- Commented-out code — delete it, git remembers.
- TODO/FIXME unless tied to a ticket: `// TODO(JIRA-456): remove after migration`.

## GoDoc (Go-specific)
Only write GoDoc comments on exported symbols, and only when the name alone isn't enough:
```go
// Paginator fetches results in pages to avoid loading large datasets into memory.
type Paginator struct { ... }

// No comment needed — name is self-documenting
func (p *Paginator) NextPage() ([]Result, error) { ... }
```

## The Test
Before adding a comment, ask:
- Can I rename something to make this obvious?
- Can I extract a helper with a descriptive name?
- If neither works — then comment.